-- Italian Stocks Slip; Ansaldo, Autogrill, Fondiaria, Maire, Parmalat Move
-- Francesca Angelini
-- 2010-07-28T16:25:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-28/italian-stocks-slip-ansaldo-autogrill-fondiaria-maire-parmalat-move.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB  Index
fell 76.02, or 0.4 percent, to 21,082.06 at 17:30 p.m. in Milan.  
 The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  
 Ansaldo STS SpA  (STS IM) sank 45 cents, or 4.2 percent, to
10.32 euros, extending yesterday’s loss of 8.3 percent.
Cheuvreux downgraded Finmeccanica SpA’s railway-technology unit
to “underperform” from “outperform,” while Exane BNP Paribas
removed the stock from its “mid-caps list” after the company
revised its full-year guidance down.  
 Separately, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Natixis Securities
trimmed their price estimates to 15.4 euros from 15.42 euros and
to 12 euros from 13.3 euros, respectively.  
 Autogrill SpA  (AGL IM) declined for a third day, losing
25.5 cents, or 2.6 percent, to 9.72 euros. Exane BNP Paribas
reiterated an “underperform” recommendation on the world’s
biggest manager of airport and highway restaurants, saying
“Autogrill’s valuation remains full in our view.” The
brokerage lifted its price estimate to 9 euros from 8.5 euros to
“reflect recent forex moves.”  
 Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA  (BMPS IM) gained 1.3
cent, or 1.3 percent, to 1.01 euros, a third consecutive
increase. Deutsche Bank AG upgraded the European banking
industry to “neutral” from “underweight,” saying that
“worries over leverage ratios, funding, and liquidity
requirements are now much reduced.”  
 Davide Campari-Milano SpA  (CPR IM), the maker of Skyy vodka
and Wild Turkey bourbon, dropped 7.75 cents, or 1.9 percent, to
4.1 euros. Deutsche Bank downgraded the European food and
beverage industry to “neutral” from “overweight.”  
 Parmalat SpA  (PLT IM), Italy’s biggest dairy company,
retreated 4.7 cents, or 2.4 percent, to 1.93 euros.  
 Fondiara-Sai SpA  (FSA IM) increased 33.5 cents, or 4.2
percent, to 8.42 euros. “Shares of Italy’s second-biggest
insurer are benefitting from some short covering ahead of next
week’s results,” said  Gabriele Roghi , head of portfolio
management at Invest Banca SpA in Empoli.  
 Hera SpA  (HER IM) gained 4.2 cents, or 3 percent, to 1.46
euros, a fifth straight increase. The regional utility said it
was selling a 20 percent stake in Herambiente for 105.6 million
euros ($137.22 million.)  
 Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) lost for the first time this
week, falling 3.25 cents, or 1.3 percent, to 2.57 euros. The
lender is conducting due diligence at Poland’s Bank Zachodni WBK
SA, a unit that parent Allied Irish Banks Plc is selling,
spokeswoman  Francesca Palermo Patera  said today by phone.  
 Intesa Chief Executive Officer Corrardo Passera said the
due diligence is “going well,” according to Palermo Patera.  
 Maire Tecnimont SpA  (MT IM) climbed 13.5 cents, or 4.9
percent, to 2.89 euros, the highest in more than a month. The
company won a $400 million contract to provide services in
Kuwait to the Kuwait National Petroleum Company.  
 Prysmian SpA  (PRY IM), the world’s second-biggest cable
maker, fell 14 cents, or 1.1 percent to 13.04 euros. Nexans SA,
the world’s biggest maker of cables and wires, is closing plants
in Italy to slash costs following a slump in construction that
was accentuated by poor weather in Europe earlier this year.  
 Saras SpA  (SRS IM) fell for a second day this week, losing
4.9 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 1.52 euros. BofA Merrill Lynch
Global Research downgraded the stock to “underperform” from
“neutral,” saying it expects “another lackluster result,
including a refining loss,” when Saras reports its earnings on
Aug. 10.  
 The owner of the largest oil refinery in the Mediterranean
also had its price estimate trimmed to 2 euros from 2.1 euros at
Goldman Sachs and to 1.5 euros from 1.65 euros at Cheuvreux.  
 Telecom Italia SpA  (TIT IM), Italy’s biggest phone company,
advanced 2.2 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 1 euro, the highest since
May 20. Telefonica SA reached an initial agreement to buy
Portugal Telecom SGPS SA’s stake in Brazil’s Vivo Participacoes
SA after raising its bid a third time to 7.5 billion euros,
people close to the talks said.  
 The deal highlights Brazil’s potential value, Intermonte
Sim SpA said in a note.  
